Defendant Jermela J Kittler in court.  Attorney Katherine Graber in court for Jermela J Kittler.  Attorney Samuel E. Simpson in court for State of Wisconsin. Sentencing hearing proceeded. Statements by State, Defense Counsel, and Defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:
Court ordered Defendant to serve 12 MONTHS in the House of Correction, with credit for 3 DAYS time served. Court STAYED the sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 2 YEARS.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION: 
- Court stayed 60 days condition time in the House of Correction to be used at the discretion of the agent.
- Complete a drivers license safety program.
- Court orders a 6 month drivers license revocation. 
- Maintain full-time enrollment in school.
- Complete anger management therapy.
- Complete a restorative justice program.
- Complete a cognitive intervention program.
- Complete 80 hours of community service. 
- NO CONTACT with I.K. or T.G.
- Submit letters of apology to social worker on JV case.

- Defendant is to provide a DNA sample and pay the DNA surcharge.
- Pay ALL MANDATORY costs, fees, and surcharges during the term of probation. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
*Court sets restitution at $4,898.00 payable to I.K,. and $500.00 payable to T.G.

*Court GRANTS expungement upon successful completion of probation.

*Court advised defendant of right to seek post conviction relief.
*Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.

Defendant Jermela J Kittler in court.  Attorney Katherine Graber in court for Jermela J Kittler.  Attorney Samuel E. Simpson in court for State of Wisconsin. 

Case in court for a final pre-trial.  State filed Amended Information.  Defense counsel acknowledges receipt of Amended Information, waives formal reading, and pleads not guilty on behalf of the defendant.  

...
Parties have reached an agreement.  Court found the State has satisfied victims' rights law.  Plea negotiations set forth on the record and agreed upon by the parties.

AS TO COUNT 1:
Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements/Jury Instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon, she may never own or possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that she may not vote until her civil rights have been restored. 

Parties request a separate date for sentencing.  Court scheduled the matter as requested and vacates jury status and jury trial dates.  Court advised defendant that all conditions of bail remain in full force effect.  Case adjourned to Branch 36, Rm 316 SB.
Sentencing hearing scheduled for October 12, 2022 at 02:00 pm.
